  <div class="topic">
    <h4>Structure</h4>
    <p>HTML elements build both the content structure of a webpage.</p>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-25-at-1.29.36-PM.png">

    <p>Copy and paste the code below inside of the <strong>body</strong> of your <strong>index.html</strong> file and then open it in your browser.</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">h1</span>></span>This is the Main Heading<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">h1</span>></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>This text might be an introduction to the ret of the page. And if the page is a long one it might be split up into several sub-headings.<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>

<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">h2</span>></span>This is a Sub-Heading<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">h2</span>></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>Many long articles have sub-headings so to help you follow the structure of what is being written. There may even be sub-sub-headings (or lower-level headings).<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>

<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">h2</span>></span>Another Sub-Heading<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">h2</span>></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>Here you can see another sub-heading.<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>
</pre>

    <p>Notice how each element takes up the entire width of the page. This is heading tags and paragraph tags are both "block-level" elements. In other words they take up the entire width of their parent elements (in this case, their parent is the body tag).</p>

    <p>Now change your HTML to look like this and open it in your browser:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">h1</span>></span>This is the Main Heading<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">h1</span>></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>This text might be an introduction to the ret of the page. And if the page is a long one it might be split up into several sub-headings.<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>

<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">h2</span>></span>This is a Sub-Heading<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">h2</span>></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>Many long articles have sub-headings so to help you follow the structure of what is being written. There may even be sub-sub-headings (or lower-level headings).<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>

<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">h2</span>></span>Another Sub-Heading<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">h2</span>></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>Here you can see another sub-heading. <span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">span</span>></span>Span tags are inline as you can see.<span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;/<span style="color:#e0c589">span</span>></span><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">p</span>></span>
</pre>

    <p>Notice that our span tag did not take up the width of it's parent. This is because span tags are "inline" and are... well, in line.</p>
