  <div class="topic">
    <h4>The Most Common HTML Tags</h4>
    <i class="fa fa-refresh"></i>
    <p>Let's build a simple website using some of the most common HTML. Let's make a website about Tel Aviv, much like <a href="https://www.secrettelaviv.com" target="_blank">Secret Tel Aviv</a>. This is what the landing page will look like when we're done over the next couple of days:</p>

    <img src="http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-27-at-8.27.54-PM.png">


    First, clear away all the HTML inside your body tag so we can start fresh.</p>

    <p class="def"><strong>The Nav</strong></p>
    <p>First let's start by building the HTML for our nav. We'll do this by using the "nav" tag.</p>
    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">nav</span>>&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">nav</span>></span></pre>

    <p>Navs work like any other "div" (generic divider), but it's used specifically for the page's naviation.</p>

    <p>Inside of the nav, let's used an unordered list for the links to our pages. Add the following HTML to your page inside the body:</p>
    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">nav</span>></span>
  <span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">ul</span>></span>
    <span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">li</span>></span><span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">a</span> <span style="color:#e0c589">href</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"#food"</span>></span>Food<span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;/<span style="color:#e0c589">a</span>></span><span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;/<span style="color:#e0c589">li</span>></span>
    <span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">li</span>></span><span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">a</span> <span style="color:#e0c589">href</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"#night-life"</span>></span>Night Life<span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;/<span style="color:#e0c589">a</span>></span><span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;/<span style="color:#e0c589">li</span>></span>
    <span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">li</span>></span><span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">a</span> <span style="color:#e0c589">href</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"#jobs"</span>></span>Jobs<span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;/<span style="color:#e0c589">a</span>></span><span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;/<span style="color:#e0c589">li</span>></span>
    <span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">li</span>></span><span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">a</span> <span style="color:#e0c589">href</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"#apartments"</span>></span>Apartments<span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;/<span style="color:#e0c589">a</span>></span><span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;/<span style="color:#e0c589">li</span>></span>
  <span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">ul</span>></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">nav</span>></span>
</pre>

    <i class="fa fa-github commit"></i>

    <p>The <strong>ul</strong> stands for "unordered list" and each <strong>li</strong> is a "list item". Inside each list item we have a link to a different section of our website. We used the <strong>a</strong> tag which takes one attribute, <strong>href</strong> followed by the destination of the link. Here we'll link to another part of our page. We'll go over that later.</p>

    <hr>
    
    <p class="def"><strong>Sections</strong></p>
    <p>We'll add some style later. Let's move on. Below the "nav" we see a large are with our title and a cool background image. This is a significant "section" of our page, so we'll use a <strong>section</strong> tag. The <strong>section</strong> tag also works just like any ordinary "div", but is more specific in it's use.</p>

    <p>Add the following HTML below your nav:</p>
    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">section</span> <span style="color:#89bdff">class</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"hero"</span>></span>
  <span style="color:#e0c589">&lt;<span style="color:#e0c589">img</span> <span style="color:#e0c589">class</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"hero-image"</span> <span style="color:#e0c589">src</span>=<span style="color:#65b042">"http://www.elevationacademy.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/logo_after_effect.png"</span>></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">section</span>></span>
</pre>

    <i class="fa fa-github commit"></i>

    <p>We gave our section a class of "hero" becuase it contains our <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hero_image" target="_blank">"hero image"</a>. Then, inside our section we used an "image tag". The "image tag" takes one attribute, "src" (source) with a URL or filepath of where the image is stored. Additionally, we gave it a class of "hero-image" to reference it later when we add CSS.</p>

